# UI Rendering Strategy & Component Delivery

When generating or refactoring UI, preserve LCP and TTFB by defaulting to server-rendered structure.

- Default to SSR/SSG for initial page loads, layout shells, and above-the-fold content.
- Never use CSR for initial structural rendering.
- Reserve client rendering for truly interactive leaves only: active state management, complex data flows (for example high-volume tabular UI), Canvas/WebGL, and animation-heavy interfaces.
- Keep hydration boundaries tight: when a Client Component is required inside a server-rendered page, isolate it as a distinct leaf component.
- Keep server pages/layouts mostly declarative and data-fetching oriented; avoid pulling large client trees into top-level shells.

## Examples

```tsx
// ❌ BAD: Client rendering controls the whole page shell
"use client";
export default function DashboardPage() {
  return <main><Header /><Hero /><InteractiveTable /></main>;
}
```

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD: Server-rendered shell with leaf client interactivity
import InteractiveTable from "./interactive-table";

export default async function DashboardPage() {
  return (
    <main>
      <Header />
      <Hero />
      <InteractiveTable />
    </main>
  );
}
```

```tsx
// interactive-table.tsx
"use client";
// Client-only logic remains isolated here.
```
